AU-2 and AU-3 work together to define **what events to audit** and **what information each audit record must contain**, forming the foundation of the audit and accountability function.

**AU-2 (Event Logging)** establishes the organizational process for identifying auditable events. Its control enhancements were incorporated into other controls (e.g., AU-12 and AC-6(9)), and it references [OMB A-130] and [SP 800-92] as guiding references [1]. AU-2 defines the event types that feed directly into AU-12, which requires audit record generation capability "for the event types the system is capable of auditing as defined in AU-2a" and generation of audit records "for the event types defined in AU-2c that include the audit record content defined in AU-3" [2].

**AU-3 (Content of Audit Records)** ensures that audit records contain sufficient information to support accountability by requiring that each record establish [7]:

- **a.** What type of event occurred;
- **b.** When the event occurred;
- **c.** Where the event occurred;
- **d.** Source of the event;
- **e.** Outcome of the event; and
- **f.** Identity of any individuals, subjects, or objects/entities associated with the event.

This content includes "event descriptions, time stamps, source and destination addresses, user or process identifiers, success or fail indications, and filenames involved" [7]. AU-3 also notes that organizations must consider how audit records could reveal personally identifiable information and mitigate associated privacy risks [7].

Together, AU-2 determines **which events** are logged, while AU-3 ensures those logs contain **sufficient detail** to reconstruct events and support accountability. AU-12 operationalizes both by generating the actual audit records [2].
